{"title_page": "1896 Dartmouth football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox college sports team season\n| mode = football\n| year = 1896\n| team = Dartmouth\n| conference = Triangular Football League\n| short_conf = TFL\n| record = 5\u20132\u20131\n| conf_record = 2\u20130\n| head_coach = [[William Wurtenburg]]\n| hc_year = 2nd\n| captain = [[Walter McCornack]]\n| stadium = Unknown\n| champion = champion\n}}\n{{1896 Triangular Football League standings}}\nThe '''1896 Dartmouth football team''' represented [[Dartmouth College]] in the [[1896 college football season]].<ref>[http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/div_iaa/ivyleague/dartmouth/1895-1899_yearly_results.php 1896 Dartmouth College football scores and results] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208052324/http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/div_iaa/ivyleague/dartmouth/1895-1899_yearly_results.php |date=December 8, 2015 }}. [[College Football Data Warehouse]]. Retrieved on October 4, 2013.</ref>\n\nThe number of games played in 1896 was reduced from the previous season, down to a more normal level of eight. One notable absence from the 1896 schedule was a game against rival Harvard, the only time during Wurtenburg's tenure that the Crimson were not played.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Staff writer |date=November 13, 1908 |title=At The Adams House: Harvard-Dartmouth Series |journal=[[The Dartmouth]] |pages=184\u2013185 |volume=XXX |issue=15 |OCLC=6311027}}</ref> The 1896 season was also the most successful, [[winning percentage]]-wise during Wurtenburg's time as coach; the team finished the year with a 5\u20132\u20131 record and a .688 win percentage, the tenth best record in the country out of the thirty major teams.<ref name=\"1896 Sports\">{{cite web |author=Staff |year=2014 |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/dartmouth/1896-schedule.html |title=Schedule & Results{{ndash}}8 Games |work=1896 Dartmouth Big Green Schedule and Results |publisher=[[Sports-Reference.com|College Football at Sports-Reference.com]] |accessdate=December 4, 2014}}</ref> Following an initial win against the [[Worcester, Massachusetts|Worcester]] Athletic Association, the squad suffered back-to-back shutout losses to [[1896 Yale Bulldogs football team|Yale]] and [[1896 Penn Quakers football team|Penn]]. The remainder of the season, however, was highly successful for the team, and they went 4\u20130\u20131 in their final five games. This included defeating both Triangular Football League opponents by a combined score of 42\u20130 for a fourth consecutive championship, and a tie with the Brown team they had lost to the previous year.<ref>{{cite web|ref=TFL |author=Staff |year=2013 |url=http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/conference_champs/champions.php?conid=525 |title=Triangular Football League{{ndash}}Conference Championships |work=Conference Championships Index |publisher=College Football Data Warehouse |accessdate=April 22, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715170823/http://cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/conference_champs/champions.php?conid=525 |archivedate=July 15, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"1896 games\">{{cite web|author=Staff |year=2013 |url=http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/coaching/alltime_coach_game_by_game.php?coachid=2585&year=1896 |title=William Wurtenburg coaching record{{ndash}}1896 |work=William C. \"Bill\" Wurtenburg Records by Year |publisher=College Football Data Warehouse |accessdate=December 4, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424193155/http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/coaching/alltime_coach_game_by_game.php?coachid=2585&year=1896 |archivedate=April 24, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 3\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| away = y\n| opponent = Worcester Athletic Association\n| site_stadium = Unknown\n| site_cityst = [[Worcester, Massachusetts|Worcester, MA]]\n| score = 30\u20130\n}}\n|{{C