{"title_page": "Boss (video games)", "text_new": "{{Original research|date=April 2020}}\n{{redirect|Boss level|the film|Boss Level}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:King_Dedede.png|thumb|[[King Dedede]], a boss from the [[Kirby (series)|''Kirby'' series]] of video games owned by [[Nintendo]]. |alt=]]\n\n{{Original research|date=August 2014}}\n{{redirect|Boss level|the film|Boss Level}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n[[File:Guacamelee! screenshot E.jpg|thumb|right|A boss fight from ''[[Guacamelee!]]'', a game in the [[metroidvania]] genre, in which the player characters (the two characters in [[luchador]] outfits) must keep ahead of the giant rampaging creature (boss) on the left, while dodging obstacles and other enemies.]]\n\nIn [[video game|video games]], a '''boss''' is a significant computer-controlled enemy.<ref>Burt, Andy (2008\u20134). \"No More Heroes: The Killer Boss Guide\". ''[[GamePro]]''. vol. 235. p. 66.</ref> A fight with a boss character is commonly referred to as a '''boss battle''' or '''boss fight'''. Boss battles are generally seen at a climax of a particular section of the game, usually at the end of a [[level (video gaming)|level or stage]], or guarding a specific objective; the boss enemy is generally far stronger than the opponents the [[player (game)|player]] has faced up to that point and is usually faced solo. A [[Boss (video gaming)#Miniboss|'''miniboss''']] is a boss weaker or less significant than the main boss in the same area or level, though more powerful than the standard enemies and often fought alongside them. A '''[[Boss (video gaming)#Superboss|superboss]]''' (sometimes 'secret' or 'hidden' boss) is generally much more powerful than the bosses encountered as part of the main game's plot and often an optional encounter. A '''[[Boss_(video_gaming)#Final_boss|final boss]]''' is often the main [[antagonist]] of a game's story and the defeat of that character provides a positive conclusion to the game.\n\nFor example, in a [[Run and gun game|run 'n' gun]] video game all regular enemies might use pistols while the boss uses a machine gun. A boss enemy is quite often larger in size than other enemies and the [[player character]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Schroder|first=Ben |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/the-top-7big-bosses/ |title=The Top 7... Big Bosses|date=15 November 2006|website=[[GamesRadar+]]|access-date=6 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140308223331/http://www.gamesradar.com/the-top-7big-bosses/ |archive-date=8 March 2014 }}</ref> At times, bosses are very hard, even impossible, to defeat without being adequately prepared and/or knowing the correct fighting approach. Bosses take strategy and special knowledge to defeat, such as how to attack weak points or avoid specific attacks.\n\nBosses are common in many genres of video games, but they are especially common in story-driven titles. [[Role-playing video game|RPGs]], [[FPS game|FPSs]], [[Platform game|platform games]], [[Fighting game|fighting games]] and [[shoot'em ups]] are particularly associated with boss battles. They may be less common in [[puzzle games]], card video games, [[Sports game|sports games]], and [[simulation games]]. The first game to feature a boss fight was the 1975 RPG [[Dnd (video game)|dnd]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/features/2015/9/28/9333685/annotated-history-boss-battles|title=An annotated history of video game boss battles|last=Lee|first=Tyler|date=2015-09-28|website=Polygon|language=en|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref> The concept has expanded to new genres, like [[Rhythm game|rhythm games]], where there may be a \"boss song\" that is more difficult. In [[Multiplayer online battle arena|MOBA]] games, defeating a map boss usually requires help from the other players, but it brings various benefits to the team, such as buffs, or lane push power.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pages.firstblood.io/pages/blog/dota-2/roshan-dota-2-guide/|title=Roshan Dota 2 Guide|date=2018-10-17|website=FirstBlood\u00ae|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://team-dignitas.net/articles/blogs/Heroes-Of-The-Storm/11768/heroes-of-the-storm-how-to-fully-utilize-mercenary-camps|title=Heroes of the Storm: How to Fully Utilize Boss and Mercenary Camps - Articles - Dignitas|last=|first=|date=|website=team-dignitas.net|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref> Some games, such as ''[[Cuphead]]'' and ''[[Warning Forever]],'' are centered around continual boss fights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/10/07/cuphead-review-a-uniquely-beautiful-and-worthwhile-challenge/|title=Cuphead review \u2014 a uniquely beautiful and worthwhile challenge|date=2017-10-07|website=VentureBeat|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.firstpersonscholar.com/warning-forever/|title=Warning Forever \u2013 First Person Scholar|website=www.firstpersonscholar.com|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe first interactive game to feature a boss was ''[[dnd (video game)|dnd]]'', a 1975 [[role-playing video game]] for the [[PLATO (computer system)|PLATO system]].<ref name=\"armory\">{{cite web|url=http://www.armory.com/~dlp/dnd1.html|title=Gary Whisenhunt, Ray Wood, Dirk Pellett, and Flint Pellett's DND|website=Armory.com|access-date=2008-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\"uvl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uvlist.net/game-160118|title=dnd (The Game of Dungeons)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071113074824/http://uvlist.net/game-160118 |archive-date=13 November 2007|website=Universal Videogame List|access-date=2008-04-09}}</ref> One of the earliest [[dungeon crawl]]s, dnd implemented many of the core concepts behind ''[[Dungeons & Dragons]]''.<ref name=\"uvl\"/> The objective of the game is to retrieve an \"Orb\" from the bottommost dungeon.<ref>{{cite web|last=Barton|first=Matt |date=23 February 2007|url= https://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/132024/the_history_of_computer_.php?page=2 |title=The History of Computer Role-Playing Games Part 1: The Early Years (1980\u20131983)|website=[[Gamasutra]]|access-date=2019-03-05}}</ref> The orb is kept in a treasure room guarded by a high-level enemy named the Gold Dragon. Only by defeating the Dragon can the player claim the orb, complete the game, and be eligible to appear on the [[high score]] list.<ref name=\"armory\"/>\n\nA 1980 example is the [[fixed shooter]] ''[[Phoenix (video game)|Phoenix]]'', wherein the player ship must fight a giant [[mothership]] in the fifth and final level.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sterbakov|first=Hugh|date=5 March 2008|url= http://www.gamepro.com/gamepro/domestic/games/features/166668.shtml |title= The 47 Most Diabolical Video-Game Villains of All Time|website=GamePro|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080309131244/http://www.gamepro.com/gamepro/domestic/games/features/166668.shtml|archive-date=2008-03-09|access-date=2008-04-28}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\nBosses are usually more difficult than regular enemies, can sustain more damage, and are generally found at the end of a level or area.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.slate.com/id/2100116/ | title=Tough Love: Can a video game be too hard? | last=Thompson | first=Clive | work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] | accessdate=1 March 2009 | date=6 May 2004 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210210016/http://www.slate.com/id/2100116/ | archive-date=10 February 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"NGen15\">{{cite magazine|last= |first= |title=The Next Generation 1996 Lexicon A to Z|magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=15 |publisher=[[Imagine Media]]|date=March 1996|page=30}}</ref> While most games include a mixture of boss opponents and regular opponents, some games have only regular opponents and some games have only bosses (e.g. ''[[Shadow of the Colossus]]'').<ref name=\"ignreview\">{{cite web |last=Roper |first=Chris |date=17 October 2005 |title=Shadow of the Colossus Review |url=http://ps2.ign.com/articles/658/658991p1.html |work=[[IGN]] |accessdate=2014-11-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120531203532/http://ps2.ign.com/articles/658/658991p1.html |archive-date=31 May 2012}}</ref> Some bosses are encountered several times through a single game, typically with alternate attacks and a different strategy required to defeat it each time.<ref name=\"NGen15\"/>  A boss battle can also be made more challenging if the boss in question becomes progressively stronger and/or less vulnerable as their [[health (gaming)|health]] decreases, requiring players to use different strategies to win. Some bosses may contain or be composed of smaller parts that can be destroyed by the player in battle, which may or may not grant an advantage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.firstpersonscholar.com/warning-forever/|title=Warning Forever \u2013 First Person Scholar|website=www.firstpersonscholar.com|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> In games such as ''[[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]'' and ''[[Castlevania: Order of Ecclesia]]'', an enemy may be introduced via a boss battle, but later appear as a regular enemy, after the player has become stronger or had a chance to find more powerful weaponry.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} \n\nBoss battles are typically seen as dramatic events. As such, they are usually characterized by unique music and [[cutscene]]s before and after the boss battle. Recurring bosses and final bosses may have their own specific [[theme music]] to distinguish them from other boss battles. This concept extends beyond combat-oriented video games. For example, a number of titles in the ''[[Dance Dance Revolution (series)|Dance Dance Revolution]]'' [[rhythm game]] series contain \"boss songs\" that are called \"bosses\" because they are exceptionally difficult to perform on.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dodson|first= Joe |date=15 October 2007 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/dance-dance-revolution-supernova-2-review/1900-6181073/|title=Dance Dance Revolution: SuperNOVA 2 Review|website=[[GameSpot]]|access-date=2019-03-05}}</ref>\n\n==Specific boss types==\n\n===Miniboss===\n[[File:Broforce_miniboss_animated.gif|thumb|right|Miniboss in the 2015 video game ''[[Broforce]]'', a [[Run-and-gun platform game|run-and-gun platformer]]]]\n<!--Please do not list every single miniboss for every single video game series in this section, notable or not.-->\nA miniboss, also known as a \"middle boss\", \"mid-boss\", \"half-boss\", \"sub-boss\",<ref>{{cite magazine |title=The Next Generation 1996 Lexicon A to Z: Sub-boss|magazine=Next Generation|issue=15 |publisher=Imagine Media|date=March 1996|page=41}}</ref> or \"semi-boss\", is a boss weaker or less significant than the main boss in the same area or level. Some minibosses are stronger versions of regular enemies, as in the [[Kirby (series)|''Kirby'']] games.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} Other video game characters who usually take the role of a miniboss are the [[Koopalings]] (''[[Super Mario]]'' series), Vile (''[[Mega Man X]]'' series), Allen O'Neil ([[Metal Slug (series)|''Metal Slug'']]), and Dark Link (''[[The Legend of Zelda]]'' series, though he appears as a final boss in ''[[Zelda II: The Adventure of Link]]''). There is also a subtype nicknamed the \"Wolfpack Boss\", for its similarity to a pack of [[wolves]], often consisting of a group of strong normal enemies that are easy to defeat on their own, but a group of them can be as difficult as a boss battle.\n\n=== Superboss ===\nA superboss is a type of boss most commonly found in [[Role-playing video game|role-playing video games]]. They are considered optional enemies, though optional bosses are not all superbosses and do not have to be defeated to complete the game. They are generally much more powerful than the bosses encountered as part of the main game's plot or [[quest (gaming)|quest]], more difficult even than the final boss, and often the player is required to complete a sidequest or the entire game to fight the superboss. For example, in ''[[Final Fantasy VII]]'', the player may choose to seek out and fight the Ruby and Emerald Weapons. Some superbosses will take the place of the final boss if certain requirements are met. This is common in [[fighting game]]s such as [[Akuma (Street Fighter)|Akuma]] in ''[[Super Street Fighter II Turbo]]''. Some superbosses can also yield special [[item (gaming)|items]] or skills that cannot be found any other way that can give a player a significant advantage during playthrough of the rest of the game, such as added experience or an extremely powerful weapon. For example, the \"raid bosses\" from ''[[Borderlands 2]]'' give rare loot unavailable anywhere else. Some superbosses in [[Online game|online games]] have an immense amount of health and must be defeated within a [[time limit (video gaming)|time limit]] by having [[Raid (gaming)|a large number of players or parties working together to defeat the boss]]. Examples of such superbosses can be found in games like ''[[Shadow Fight 2]]'' and ''[[Star Wars: Galaxy of Heroes]]''. [[Toby Fox]]'s games ''[[Undertale]]'' and ''[[Deltarune]]'' both feature superbosses in the form of Sans the Skeleton (only accessible by making it to the end of ''Undertale'''s \"Genocide Route\") and Jevil (only accessible by locating a set of keys to free him from a prison cell), respectively.\n\n===Final boss===\n<!--Please do not list every single final boss for every single video game series in this section, notable or not.-->\n\nThe final boss, or end boss,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2012/06/13/know-your-lore-the-true-end-boss-of-mists-of-pandaria/|title=Know Your Lore: The true end boss of Mists of Pandaria?|last=Rossi|first=Matthew|date=13 June 2012|website=[[Engadget]]|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref> is typically present at, or near, the end of a game, with completion of the game's storyline usually following victory in the battle.{{r|scorpia199408}}<ref name=\"kaiser20100713\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/video-games/issues/issue_262/7811-Stop-Killing-the-Foozle |title=Stop Killing the Foozle! |last=Kaiser |first=Rowan |date=13 July 2010 |work=[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]] |access-date=2017-12-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222053323/http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/video-games/issues/issue_262/7811-Stop-Killing-the-Foozle |archive-date=22 December 2017}}</ref> The final boss is usually the main antagonist of the game; however, there are exceptions, such as in ''[[Conker's Bad Fur Day]]'', where the final boss is the antagonist's alien pet. Final bosses are generally larger, more detailed, and better animated than lesser enemies, often in order to inspire a feeling of grandeur and special significance from the encounter.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn some games, a hidden boss, referred to as the \"true\" final boss, is present. These bosses only appear after the completion of specific additional levels, choosing specific dialogue options, or after obtaining a particular item or set of items, such as the Chaos Emeralds in the ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' series, or doing a series of tasks in ''[[Metal Gear Solid: Peace Walker]]''. These bosses are generally more difficult to defeat. In games with a \"true\" final boss, victory leads to either a better ending or a more detailed version of the regular ending. Examples of a \"true final boss\" include the Radiance in ''[[Hollow Knight]]'', Indalecio in ''[[Star Ocean: The Second Story]]'', and the Moon Presence in ''[[Bloodborne]]''.\n\n'''Foozle''' describes a [[clich\u00e9]] final boss that exists only to act as the final problem before a player can complete the game.<ref>{{Cite web |author=Scorpia |url=http://www.scorpia.com/?p=1510#more-1510 |title=Looking Evil|work=Scorpia's Gaming Lair |date=20 May 2009|access-date=11 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407125811/http://www.scorpia.com/?p=1510#more-1510#more-1510 |archive-date=7 April 2016}}</ref>{{r|kaiser20100713}} [[Scorpia (journalist)|Scorpia]] stated in 1994 that \"about 98% of all [[role-playing video games]] can be summed up as follows: 'We go out and bash on critters until we're strong enough to go bash on Foozle.'\"<ref name=\"scorpia199408\">{{Cite magazine|author=Scorpia|authorlink=Scorpia (journalist)|date=August 1994|title=Scorpia The Avatar|url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1994&pub=2&id=121|url-status=live|department=Scorpia's Sting|magazine=[[Computer Gaming World]]|issue=121|pages=29\u201333|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180102213537/http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1994&pub=2&id=121|archive-date=2 January 2018|access-date=21 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Glossary of video game terms]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boss (Video Gaming)}}\n[[Category:Video game bosses| ]]\n[[Category:Video game terminology]]\n[[Category:Words and phrases introduced in 1975]]\n", "text_old": "{{Original research|date=August 2014}}\n{{redirect|Boss level|the film|Boss Level}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n[[File:Guacamelee! screenshot E.jpg|thumb|right|A boss fight from ''[[Guacamelee!]]'', a game in the [[metroidvania]] genre, in which the player characters (the two characters in [[luchador]] outfits) must keep ahead of the giant rampaging creature (boss) on the left, while dodging obstacles and other enemies.]]\n\nIn [[video game|video games]], a '''boss''' is a significant computer-controlled enemy.<ref>Burt, Andy (2008\u20134). \"No More Heroes: The Killer Boss Guide\". ''[[GamePro]]''. vol. 235. p. 66.</ref> A fight with a boss character is commonly referred to as a '''boss battle''' or '''boss fight'''. Boss battles are generally seen at a climax of a particular section of the game, usually at the end of a [[level (video gaming)|level or stage]], or guarding a specific objective; the boss enemy is generally far stronger than the opponents the [[player (game)|player]] has faced up to that point and is usually faced solo. A [[Boss (video gaming)#Miniboss|'''miniboss''']] is a boss weaker or less significant than the main boss in the same area or level, though more powerful than the standard enemies and often fought alongside them. A '''[[Boss (video gaming)#Superboss|superboss]]''' (sometimes 'secret' or 'hidden' boss) is generally much more powerful than the bosses encountered as part of the main game's plot and often an optional encounter. A '''[[Boss_(video_gaming)#Final_boss|final boss]]''' is often the main [[antagonist]] of a game's story and the defeat of that character provides a positive conclusion to the game.\n\nFor example, in a [[Run and gun game|run 'n' gun]] video game all regular enemies might use pistols while the boss uses a machine gun. A boss enemy is quite often larger in size than other enemies and the [[player character]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Schroder|first=Ben |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/the-top-7big-bosses/ |title=The Top 7... Big Bosses|date=15 November 2006|website=[[GamesRadar+]]|access-date=6 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140308223331/http://www.gamesradar.com/the-top-7big-bosses/ |archive-date=8 March 2014 }}</ref> At times, bosses are very hard, even impossible, to defeat without being adequately prepared and/or knowing the correct fighting approach. Bosses take strategy and special knowledge to defeat, such as how to attack weak points or avoid specific attacks.\n\nBosses are common in many genres of video games, but they are especially common in story-driven titles. [[Role-playing video game|RPGs]], [[FPS game|FPSs]], [[Platform game|platform games]], [[Fighting game|fighting games]] and [[shoot'em ups]] are particularly associated with boss battles. They may be less common in [[puzzle games]], card video games, [[Sports game|sports games]], and [[simulation games]]. The first game to feature a boss fight was the 1975 RPG [[Dnd (video game)|dnd]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/features/2015/9/28/9333685/annotated-history-boss-battles|title=An annotated history of video game boss battles|last=Lee|first=Tyler|date=2015-09-28|website=Polygon|language=en|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref> The concept has expanded to new genres, like [[Rhythm game|rhythm games]], where there may be a \"boss song\" that is more difficult. In [[Multiplayer online battle arena|MOBA]] games, defeating a map boss usually requires help from the other players, but it brings various benefits to the team, such as buffs, or lane push power.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pages.firstblood.io/pages/blog/dota-2/roshan-dota-2-guide/|title=Roshan Dota 2 Guide|date=2018-10-17|website=FirstBlood\u00ae|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://team-dignitas.net/articles/blogs/Heroes-Of-The-Storm/11768/heroes-of-the-storm-how-to-fully-utilize-mercenary-camps|title=Heroes of the Storm: How to Fully Utilize Boss and Mercenary Camps - Articles - Dignitas|last=|first=|date=|website=team-dignitas.net|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref> Some games, such as ''[[Cuphead]]'' and ''[[Warning Forever]],'' are centered around continual boss fights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/10/07/cuphead-review-a-uniquely-beautiful-and-worthwhile-challenge/|title=Cuphead review \u2014 a uniquely beautiful and worthwhile challenge|date=2017-10-07|website=VentureBeat|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.firstpersonscholar.com/warning-forever/|title=Warning Forever \u2013 First Person Scholar|website=www.firstpersonscholar.com|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe first interactive game to feature a boss was ''[[dnd (video game)|dnd]]'', a 1975 [[role-playing video game]] for the [[PLATO (computer system)|PLATO system]].<ref name=\"armory\">{{cite web|url=http://www.armory.com/~dlp/dnd1.html|title=Gary Whisenhunt, Ray Wood, Dirk Pellett, and Flint Pellett's DND|website=Armory.com|access-date=2008-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\"uvl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uvlist.net/game-160118|title=dnd (The Game of Dungeons)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071113074824/http://uvlist.net/game-160118 |archive-date=13 November 2007|website=Universal Videogame List|access-date=2008-04-09}}</ref> One of the earliest [[dungeon crawl]]s, dnd implemented many of the core concepts behind ''[[Dungeons & Dragons]]''.<ref name=\"uvl\"/> The objective of the game is to retrieve an \"Orb\" from the bottommost dungeon.<ref>{{cite web|last=Barton|first=Matt |date=23 February 2007|url= https://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/132024/the_history_of_computer_.php?page=2 |title=The History of Computer Role-Playing Games Part 1: The Early Years (1980\u20131983)|website=[[Gamasutra]]|access-date=2019-03-05}}</ref> The orb is kept in a treasure room guarded by a high-level enemy named the Gold Dragon. Only by defeating the Dragon can the player claim the orb, complete the game, and be eligible to appear on the [[high score]] list.<ref name=\"armory\"/>\n\nA 1980 example is the [[fixed shooter]] ''[[Phoenix (video game)|Phoenix]]'', wherein the player ship must fight a giant [[mothership]] in the fifth and final level.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sterbakov|first=Hugh|date=5 March 2008|url= http://www.gamepro.com/gamepro/domestic/games/features/166668.shtml |title= The 47 Most Diabolical Video-Game Villains of All Time|website=GamePro|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080309131244/http://www.gamepro.com/gamepro/domestic/games/features/166668.shtml|archive-date=2008-03-09|access-date=2008-04-28}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\nBosses are usually more difficult than regular enemies, can sustain more damage, and are generally found at the end of a level or area.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.slate.com/id/2100116/ | title=Tough Love: Can a video game be too hard? | last=Thompson | first=Clive | work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] | accessdate=1 March 2009 | date=6 May 2004 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210210016/http://www.slate.com/id/2100116/ | archive-date=10 February 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"NGen15\">{{cite magazine|last= |first= |title=The Next Generation 1996 Lexicon A to Z|magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=15 |publisher=[[Imagine Media]]|date=March 1996|page=30}}</ref> While most games include a mixture of boss opponents and regular opponents, some games have only regular opponents and some games have only bosses (e.g. ''[[Shadow of the Colossus]]'').<ref name=\"ignreview\">{{cite web |last=Roper |first=Chris |date=17 October 2005 |title=Shadow of the Colossus Review |url=http://ps2.ign.com/articles/658/658991p1.html |work=[[IGN]] |accessdate=2014-11-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120531203532/http://ps2.ign.com/articles/658/658991p1.html |archive-date=31 May 2012}}</ref> Some bosses are encountered several times through a single game, typically with alternate attacks and a different strategy required to defeat it each time.<ref name=\"NGen15\"/>  A boss battle can also be made more challenging if the boss in question becomes progressively stronger and/or less vulnerable as their [[health (gaming)|health]] decreases, requiring players to use different strategies to win. Some bosses may contain or be composed of smaller parts that can be destroyed by the player in battle, which may or may not grant an advantage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.firstpersonscholar.com/warning-forever/|title=Warning Forever \u2013 First Person Scholar|website=www.firstpersonscholar.com|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> In games such as ''[[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]'' and ''[[Castlevania: Order of Ecclesia]]'', an enemy may be introduced via a boss battle, but later appear as a regular enemy, after the player has become stronger or had a chance to find more powerful weaponry.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} \n\nBoss battles are typically seen as dramatic events. As such, they are usually characterized by unique music and [[cutscene]]s before and after the boss battle. Recurring bosses and final bosses may have their own specific [[theme music]] to distinguish them from other boss battles. This concept extends beyond combat-oriented video games. For example, a number of titles in the ''[[Dance Dance Revolution (series)|Dance Dance Revolution]]'' [[rhythm game]] series contain \"boss songs\" that are called \"bosses\" because they are exceptionally difficult to perform on.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dodson|first= Joe |date=15 October 2007 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/dance-dance-revolution-supernova-2-review/1900-6181073/|title=Dance Dance Revolution: SuperNOVA 2 Review|website=[[GameSpot]]|access-date=2019-03-05}}</ref>\n\n==Specific boss types==\n\n===Miniboss===\n[[File:Broforce_miniboss_animated.gif|thumb|right|Miniboss in the 2015 video game ''[[Broforce]]'', a [[Run-and-gun platform game|run-and-gun platformer]]]]\n<!--Please do not list every single miniboss for every single video game series in this section, notable or not.-->\nA miniboss, also known as a \"middle boss\", \"mid-boss\", \"half-boss\", \"sub-boss\",<ref>{{cite magazine |title=The Next Generation 1996 Lexicon A to Z: Sub-boss|magazine=Next Generation|issue=15 |publisher=Imagine Media|date=March 1996|page=41}}</ref> or \"semi-boss\", is a boss weaker or less significant than the main boss in the same area or level. Some minibosses are stronger versions of regular enemies, as in the [[Kirby (series)|''Kirby'']] games.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} Other video game characters who usually take the role of a miniboss are the [[Koopalings]] (''[[Super Mario]]'' series), Vile (''[[Mega Man X]]'' series), Allen O'Neil ([[Metal Slug (series)|''Metal Slug'']]), and Dark Link (''[[The Legend of Zelda]]'' series, though he appears as a final boss in ''[[Zelda II: The Adventure of Link]]''). There is also a subtype nicknamed the \"Wolfpack Boss\", for its similarity to a pack of [[wolves]], often consisting of a group of strong normal enemies that are easy to defeat on their own, but a group of them can be as difficult as a boss battle.\n\n=== Superboss ===\nA superboss is a type of boss most commonly found in [[Role-playing video game|role-playing video games]]. They are considered optional enemies, though optional bosses are not all superbosses and do not have to be defeated to complete the game. They are generally much more powerful than the bosses encountered as part of the main game's plot or [[quest (gaming)|quest]], more difficult even than the final boss, and often the player is required to complete a sidequest or the entire game to fight the superboss. For example, in ''[[Final Fantasy VII]]'', the player may choose to seek out and fight the Ruby and Emerald Weapons. Some superbosses will take the place of the final boss if certain requirements are met. This is common in [[fighting game]]s such as [[Akuma (Street Fighter)|Akuma]] in ''[[Super Street Fighter II Turbo]]''. Some superbosses can also yield special [[item (gaming)|items]] or skills that cannot be found any other way that can give a player a significant advantage during playthrough of the rest of the game, such as added experience or an extremely powerful weapon. For example, the \"raid bosses\" from ''[[Borderlands 2]]'' give rare loot unavailable anywhere else. Some superbosses in [[Online game|online games]] have an immense amount of health and must be defeated within a [[time limit (video gaming)|time limit]] by having [[Raid (gaming)|a large number of players or parties working together to defeat the boss]]. Examples of such superbosses can be found in games like ''[[Shadow Fight 2]]'' and ''[[Star Wars: Galaxy of Heroes]]''. [[Toby Fox]]'s games ''[[Undertale]]'' and ''[[Deltarune]]'' both feature superbosses in the form of Sans the Skeleton (only accessible by making it to the end of ''Undertale'''s \"Genocide Route\") and Jevil (only accessible by locating a set of keys to free him from a prison cell), respectively.\n\n===Final boss===\n<!--Please do not list every single final boss for every single video game series in this section, notable or not.-->\n\nThe final boss, or end boss,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2012/06/13/know-your-lore-the-true-end-boss-of-mists-of-pandaria/|title=Know Your Lore: The true end boss of Mists of Pandaria?|last=Rossi|first=Matthew|date=13 June 2012|website=[[Engadget]]|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref> is typically present at, or near, the end of a game, with completion of the game's storyline usually following victory in the battle.{{r|scorpia199408}}<ref name=\"kaiser20100713\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/video-games/issues/issue_262/7811-Stop-Killing-the-Foozle |title=Stop Killing the Foozle! |last=Kaiser |first=Rowan |date=13 July 2010 |work=[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]] |access-date=2017-12-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222053323/http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/video-games/issues/issue_262/7811-Stop-Killing-the-Foozle |archive-date=22 December 2017}}</ref> The final boss is usually the main antagonist of the game; however, there are exceptions, such as in ''[[Conker's Bad Fur Day]]'', where the final boss is the antagonist's alien pet. Final bosses are generally larger, more detailed, and better animated than lesser enemies, often in order to inspire a feeling of grandeur and special significance from the encounter.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn some games, a hidden boss, referred to as the \"true\" final boss, is present. These bosses only appear after the completion of specific additional levels, choosing specific dialogue options, or after obtaining a particular item or set of items, such as the Chaos Emeralds in the ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' series, or doing a series of tasks in ''[[Metal Gear Solid: Peace Walker]]''. These bosses are generally more difficult to defeat. In games with a \"true\" final boss, victory leads to either a better ending or a more detailed version of the regular ending. Examples of a \"true final boss\" include the Radiance in ''[[Hollow Knight]]'', Indalecio in ''[[Star Ocean: The Second Story]]'', and the Moon Presence in ''[[Bloodborne]]''.\n\n'''Foozle''' describes a [[clich\u00e9]] final boss that exists only to act as the final problem before a player can complete the game.<ref>{{Cite web |author=Scorpia |url=http://www.scorpia.com/?p=1510#more-1510 |title=Looking Evil|work=Scorpia's Gaming Lair |date=20 May 2009|access-date=11 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407125811/http://www.scorpia.com/?p=1510#more-1510#more-1510 |archive-date=7 April 2016}}</ref>{{r|kaiser20100713}} [[Scorpia (journalist)|Scorpia]] stated in 1994 that \"about 98% of all [[role-playing video games]] can be summed up as follows: 'We go out and bash on critters until we're strong enough to go bash on Foozle.'\"<ref name=\"scorpia199408\">{{Cite magazine|author=Scorpia|authorlink=Scorpia (journalist)|date=August 1994|title=Scorpia The Avatar|url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1994&pub=2&id=121|url-status=live|department=Scorpia's Sting|magazine=[[Computer Gaming World]]|issue=121|pages=29\u201333|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180102213537/http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1994&pub=2&id=121|archive-date=2 January 2018|access-date=21 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Glossary of video game terms]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boss (Video Gaming)}}\n[[Category:Video game bosses| ]]\n[[Category:Video game terminology]]\n[[Category:Words and phrases introduced in 1975]]\n", "name_user": "0nelastmemory", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added an important example of a boss to this page, a more recognizable boss to help better signify the meaning of the page.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boss_(video_games)"}
