{"title_page": "Georg Brandl Egloff", "text_new": "{{short description|Film composer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Georg Brandl Egloff\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Georg Brandl Egloff\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1963|2|16|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Monterey]], [[California]], U.S.\n| occupation           = Producer, Composer \n| years_active         = 1994\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Laura Shanahan|1999|2014|end=died}}\n| children           = 2\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist | embed=yes\n| background           = solo_singer\n| genre                = {{flatlist|\n* [[Film score|Film music]]\n* [[Theme music]]\n* TV Scores\n* Commercial Scores\n}}\n| instrument           = {{flatlist|\n* [[Piano]]\n* [[Keyboard instrument|Keyboards]]\n}}\n| associated_acts      = \n| website              = \n}}\n}}\n\n'''Georg Brandl Egloff''' is an American producer and composer of music for film, television, radio, and commercials.  He has composed music for ''[[Shameless (American TV series)|Shameless]]'', ''[[The Goldbergs (2013 TV series)|The Goldbergs]]'', ''[[The West Wing]]'', and ''[[A&E Biography]]'', among others, and is credited with writing the Station ID music for the ''[[FX (channel)]]'' and the ''[[Hallmark Channel]]''.  He wrote the main theme music for ''[[This I Believe]]'' series on ''[[All Things Considered]]'' and ''[[Morning Edition]]'', and composes and produces music for ''[[Milk Street Radio]]'' and ''[[America's Test Kitchen]]'' (PBS and NPR).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R13OAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA254&lpg=PA254&dq=georg+brandl+egloff+music&source=bl&ots=yfnTfIq8lA&sig=ACfU3U1KYByNyIrLYDI9cbEQyZy5AHoNow&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwihx_meg4XoAhXEi54KHYdzD0g4ChDoATAJegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=georg%20brandl%20eglof%20music&f=false|title=This I Believe II: More Personal Philosophies of Remarkable Men and Women by Jay Allison and Dan Gediman |publisher=Henry Holt & Company |date=2008 |accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.177milkstreet.com/radio/cast|title=Christopher Kimball's Milk Street Radio Cast |publisher=Milk Street Radio |date= |accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early Life==\nGeorg Brandl Egloff was born in [[Monterey, California]] to parents, David and Susan Egloff. He grew up in Oberlin, Ohio. While still in high school, he studied composition, electronic music, and jazz piano at the [[Oberlin Conservatory of Music]].  He attended the Berklee College of Music in Boston and received a Bachelor's degree in performance and composition in 1986.\n\n==Music Career==\nEgloff moved to [[New York City]] in 1986, where he performed as a jazz pianist in [[Manhattan]]. He served as the Tuesday night pianist at the famous [[Village Gate]] club on [[Bleecker Street]]. During that period, he performed at The [[Village Vanguard]], The Blue Note, Chicago Blues, Zanzibar, The [[Knitting Factory]], and Sweet Basil, among others.  Egloff worked with many jazz and blues artists including [[Ruth Brown]] and [[Linda Hopkins]].\n\nIn the 1990s, Egloff began working in rock and pop music venues with singers including [[Jeff Buckley]], [[Joan Osborne]], [[Ronnie Spector]] and [[Johnny Thunders]]. He recorded as a session keyboardist on many projects, including work for producers [[Phil Ramone]] and [[Frank Filipetti]] and recorded a version of \"[[My Way (song)|My Way]]\" for the [[Frank Sinatra]] [[Duets (Frank Sinatra album)|''Duets'' series]]. \n\nHe scored his first short film, ''The Anniversary'', directed by Noah Kine in 1991.\n\n==Film and Television Music==\nIn 1994, Egloff was hired to write music for the A&E Biography on [[Hillary Clinton]], which led to work on twenty-two more episodes for the popular series. Soon after, he was writing music for other television documentaries, independent and short films, national commercials, and live events.  Egloff continues composing music for television, film, radio, commercials, podcasts, and other media.\n\nHe has written for ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'', ''[[The West Wing]]'', ''[[Pan Am (TV series)|Pan Am]]'', ''[[Third Watch]]'', ''[[Shameless (U.S. TV series)|Shameless]],'' and various programs airing on [[HBO]],  [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]], and [[Lifetime Television]].  His film work includes ''[[The Company Men]]'', ''The Big Time'', ''[[The Babymakers]]'', and ''[[The Terminal]]'' among others. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1241228/?ref_=nv_sr_srsg_0|title=Film and Television Credits|publisher=IMDB |date= |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Egloff appeared in an episode of ''[[The West Wing]]'' playing a Hammond organ with [[James Taylor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gettyimages.com.au/detail/news-photo/change-is-gonna-come-episode-7-aired-12-1-04-pictured-georg-news-photo/140852129|title=The West Wing - Georg Egloff performs with James Taylor |publisher=Getty Images |date=February 1, 2004 |accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>.\n\n===Filmography===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Production \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2019\n|[[The Magicians (American TV series)]]\n|Composer, Additional Music\n|[[Syfy]]\n|-\n|[[Wayne (TV series)]]\n|Composer, Additional Music\n|[[YouTube Premium]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2018\n|[[American Woman (TV series)]]\n|Composer, Additional Music\n|[[Paramount Network]]\n|-\n|[[Super Troopers 2]]\n|Composer, Arranger\n|[[Fox Searchlight Pictures]]\n|-\n|[[Shameless (American TV series)]]\n|Composer, Additional Music\n|[[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2016\n|[[The Goldbergs (season 4)]]\n|Composer, Additional Music\n|[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n|-\n|[[Shameless (American TV series)]]\n|Composer, Additional Music\n|[[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]\n|-\n|Spirit Lake Cycles\n|Composer\n|Documentary\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" |2014\n|[[Shameless (American TV series)]]\n|Composer, Additional Music\n|